    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter April 11th with a clear top-tier offensive trio anchoring the lineup: **Trea Turner** (72.23), **Yordan Alvarez** (68.04), and **Kyle Schwarber** (65.95). **Trea Turner** remains the primary engine for our stolen base strategy today; facing Pfaadt, he benefits from a favorable SP delivery profile that allows him to exploit the basepaths, compounded by a leadoff spot that maximizes his plate appearance volume. While **Yordan Alvarez** and **Kyle Schwarber** face stiffer arms, their elite xwOBA metrics and favorable batting order slots provide the high-ceiling production required to carry the team\u2019s power categories against average-to-solid pitching. **Colt Keith** also emerges as a standout start (63.90) against Junk, with his aggressive 3-hole positioning and a park environment that perfectly aligns to boost his base projection.\n\nStrategic depth remains tested, however, as evidenced by our toughest roster decisions. **Christian Yelich** barely cleared the floor (40.19) while **Josh Smith** (40.06) sits right on the precipice; both are suffering from poor SP matchups, with **Christian Yelich** specifically hampered by a negative platoon shift against the southpaw Griffin. The most agonizing omission today is **Carson Benge** (39.27). Despite his strong base profile, the combination of a difficult platoon disadvantage and a low-leverage spot in the order kept him just shy of our 40.00 efficiency mandate. We are effectively choosing to preserve our daily game caps by benching **Carson Benge** and **Victor Scott II** in favor of players with higher immediate order-based impact.\n\nManagement must remain vigilant regarding the lineup fluidity for both **Yordan Alvarez** and **Josh Smith**. We have assumed optimal placements for both, but any drop in their respective orders would necessitate a re-evaluation of their utility. Additionally, while **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (60.93) is a strong play, note that the opposing catcher\u2019s elite pop time and the pitcher's tendency to hold runners tight impose a moderate risk to his stolen base upside. We remain fully committed to the stolen base hunt, but we will not force **Victor Scott II** into the lineup when the data indicates his efficiency will fall below our replacement floor against a left-handed starter. Other depth pieces like **Kazuma Okamoto**, **Zac Veen**, **Lars Nootbaar**, **Jerar Encarnacion**, and **Luis Pena** are currently managed out of the rotation to protect our long-term cap viability.",
